title: For Sale:  H&K G36 .22 Custom Rifle
postcontent:
This is a project I did for fun a few years ago and I am ready to let it go. I took a brand new Marlin 795 and put it inside of a almost new Echo 1 H&K G36c airsoft body. I had seen these done a few times, but usually with glue and epoxy all over it. This takes down using the standard pins as it normally would, no epoxy or glue, just hand made parts and fabrication. The charging handle works as it normally would on a real G36, actually operating the slide and ejection port. The trigger is handmade to match the real thing, and works great. It still uses the stock 10rnd Marlin 795 magazines through the hole where the real mag would go, and an airsoft mag was modified to fit over it and clip in like normal to make it all look right. The folding stock works and is easily removable. THIS IS NOT A SBR THOUGH. The barrel is full length still, and with stock folded or removed the muzzle to butt length is still over federal regs. The barrel is threaded at the end, but the suppressor on the end is actually a mock airsoft suppressor bored on one end and fits over backwards, (the barrel goes all the way through and fits flush at the muzzle when screwed on tight). I have received many compliments on this gun on and off the range. It's pretty quick to take down and put back together. in fact it can only go one way, so it's fool proof. When it was built it was very reliable, but because it's so fun to shoot, the mags need new springs and the ejector on the Marlin could use replacing, THATS IT. Both very cheap and easy things to do. 

For $400, it comes with everything seen in pics. 911 tactical bag which fits it perfect, red dot sight, and collapsible bipod.

H&K USP Compact Pistol is lightly used. Shot only 2-300 FMJ rounds. It is a medium sized 9mm pistol. It is well suited for CCW use.

Based on the full-size USP models, these handy pistols combine compact size with optimum effective shooting performance. 

USP Compacts are smaller and lighter than large frame USPs. The reduction in trigger reach and grip circumference increases concealability and enhances shooting ergonomics. Unlike some subcompact semiautomatic pistols that use a difficult to shoot "two-finger grip" frame, the USP Compact uses a narrow, full-hand grip frame with a choice of interchangeable extended or flush-fitting magazine floorplates. This makes the pistol easy to shoot without sacrificing concealability.

Like their large frame predecessors, USP Compacts are designed with the demanding needs of the law enforcement and military shooters in mind. Using a modified linkless Browning-type action, the USP Compact is built to take the punishment of high-energy +P loads.

To reduce the length of the slide and barrel on the USP Compact, the mechanical recoil reduction system found on large frame USPs has been replaced by a specially designed flat compression spring contained in the captive recoil spring assembly by a polymer absorber bushing. Service life is still engineered to exceed 20,000 rounds.

Easy to shoot, simple to maintain; the USP Compact is a reliable, safe, accurate, and highly concealable pistol.

It literally just "pops" in your hands, and will put little holes on paper, right next to each other, as fast as you can pull the trigger. I know a lot of people say their rifles "recoil like a .22".. but in all honesty, my Ruger 10/22 has more recoil than this rifle. All brass lands in a neat pile about 2 feet to your 3 o'clock. I have several hundred rounds through the rifle, so it is broken in but FAR from being well used. I was ringing steel with this build as far as 540 yards as of just recently. It will devour everything from 55gr to 77gr with no problems. While the intention was for competition, I never made it beyond a few range sessions. Rather than stare at a safe queen all the time, I decided to list her up.

I used all name brand, high end parts for this build. I didn't want to leave any question to reliability or quality. This is truly breaking my heart to list this rifle up here. While I don't "need" to sell it, I think if I can get a fair price for it, the funds will serve my family better elsewhere.

All in all, I have well over $2,500 invested in this rifle. I'd like to see some return on my investment, but will discount based on use. 

You can read more about my build on this rifle, and all the work I put into it at http://forum.308ar.com/topic/2670-robocop1051s-mega-arms-billet-ambidextrous-ar15/

Beautiful, tight, perfect timing & lock-up.  These were only made for a couple of years (late 1959-early 1961) & then changed to the 18-2 & later were the -3 & -4. The screws aren't buggered & all lines & seams match perfectly.  It has adjustable sights & they have never been touched from the factory.  This gun is like brand new.  

This is a very rare gun to find in this condition.  The only trades that would interest me would be a H&R 999 4" Sportsman, a Ruger Single-six 4 5/8", .223/5.56 or 45acp ammo plus considerable cash.
